Everything he rails against in English football — the critics, the press, those who decry a destructive attitude he confuses indulgently with desire — are actually all that is good for him. Pandered to by his coach, his grateful team-mates and a slavish, cheerleading media, he is then set on a course of self-destruction.

That is the Suarez irony. He feels he punished England with the goals that ended this country’s World Cup ambitions. He feels he was avenged. Yet avenged for what, exactly?

Everything he despises about the English game is what keeps him in check. If Suarez plays no further part in this World Cup, or in football for many months to come, it will be because he failed to learn the lessons of his brief exposure to the standards of the English game.

If only he knew it, we’re the best friends he has.

